<br>
these crew could also impart their experiences on the arriving crew.  the returning members to earth would relay the science and experiences, perhaps training the next astronauts for their mission.  eventually, we could send 20 people per mission, and establish semi-permanent crew on mars, perhaps 10 year rotations in addition to shorter term rotations.  these could be our engineers and terraformers. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 3187<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/3/03 12:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=601.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: settlers vs explorers</span><hr size=1> As I've said in other threads, I'm concerned about children born into such an environment. Adults might survive a one third gravity World without complications but they have reached full maturity. Children would be growing and forming into adults without natural gravity. They would become bean stalks. The damage this could cause to the spine and organs is going to be irreversible. A couple of hours in a centrifuge each day isn't going to avert it. Their weakened systems will possibly be in permanent pain. Even if they survive, they will likely never visit Earth. <br>
<br>
It's a pity Venus can't be terraformed. Perhaps in a few million years when its crust stabilises. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 797<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/3/03 1:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=601.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: settlers vs explorers</span><hr size=1> It's more likely that our heights are determined by genetics rather than gravity.  I know it sounds cruel, but in a way I'm hoping people born on Mars won't be able to come to Earth.  This could essentially force the development of a society there and a spacefaring one at that since resources in space would be particularly valuable to them.  And the fact that it would be a lot easier to escape Martian gravity would certainly make it easier for them to be spacefarers in itself.  The big question is though, would people have children on Mars if they knew they couldn't go to Earth?  Would that even be ethical?  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nathanforst>nathan forst</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 77<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/4/03 7:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=601.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/image/planetary/mars/face.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: settlers vs explorers</span><hr size=1> I would go...but only if it were for 2-5 years. Then...after I came back to Earth I would stay here for 2 years and then go again...if need be. <br>
